1 Project: Image classification using CNNs in Keras¶

1.1 Objective¶

We are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of grown. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species. The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

4. Data Pre-Processing¶

4.1 Gaussian Blur and Normalization¶

First, we are going to use Gaussian Blurring to remove unwanted noise from the images. We are also going to normalize data between range 0 to 1 dividing by 255

In [11]:
# create empty array
data_blur = np.empty(shape=(4750, 128, 128, 3),dtype='float32')
# use gaussian blurring and normalization
for img in range(len(data)):
    data_blur[img] = cv2.GaussianBlur(data[img], (5, 5), 0) / 255.0

5.1 Functions to evaluate models¶

In [20]:
# Function to plot training results by epoch
def plot_hist(hist):
    # Capturing learning history per epoch
    hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    hist['epoch'] = history.epoch

    # Plotting loss at different epochs
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.title('Loss')
    plt.plot(hist['loss'])
    plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
    plt.legend(("train" , "valid") , loc =0);

    # Plotting recall at different epochs
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.title('Accuracy')
    plt.plot(hist['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(hist['val_accuracy'])
    plt.legend(("train" , "valid") , loc =0);
In [21]:
def metrics_score(model, model_name, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    # Evaluate model
    loss_train, accuracy_train, recall_train, precision_train = model.evaluate(X_train, y_train)
    loss_test, accuracy_test, recall_test, precision_test  = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
    # Calculate scores and save them in a dictionary
    score_dict = {'Model': model_name,
                  'Accuracy on training set' : accuracy_train,
                  'Accuracy on validation set': accuracy_test,
                  'Recall on training set' : recall_train,
                  'Recal on validation set': recall_test,
                  'Precision on training set' : precision_train,
                  'Precision on validation set': precision_test
                 }
    # Create a dataframe with scores
    scores = pd.DataFrame(score_dict,index=[0])
    # return the df
    return scores
In [22]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test):
    # Test Prediction 
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    y_test_pred_classes = np.argmax(y_test_pred, axis=1)
    # Test Accuracy 
    rounded_labels = np.array(np.argmax(y_test, axis=1))
    # Confusion matrix normalized per category true value
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(rounded_labels, y_test_pred_classes, normalize='true')
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, annot=True);

5.2 First CNN Model¶

Now, we are going to construct the first CNN model

In [23]:
# Creating earlystopping callback
early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', 
                                                  min_delta=0, 
                                                  patience=15,
                                                  verbose=0, mode='max', 
                                                  restore_best_weights= True)
In [24]:
# Initialize seed for random numbers
np.random.seed(1)
tf.random.set_seed(1)

# Sequential model
model_1 = Sequential()

# Input layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(128,128,3,)))
# Convolution layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# Global Max Pool layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.GlobalMaxPool2D())
# Flattening the data
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
# Dense layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
# Dropout layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2))
# Output Layer
model_1.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(12, activation='softmax')) # 12 predicted classes
In [25]:
# Compile the model
model_1.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy', 'Recall', 'Precision'])

Performance Analysis

  • This first model is slightly overfitting. Metrics on training set are higher than on validation set
  • The accuracy on validation set is 0.69. That means that 31% of the images are not classified correctly.
  • Images of Common-Chickweed are the best classified (98%) while Black-grass images are only classified correctly 19% of the time. It is important to point that Common-Chickweed has more than 600 images while Black-grass only has around 200 images. Therefore, there is a big unbalanced between classes.

6 Model Performance Improvement¶

We are going to try different strategies to improve the model performance:

  • Deeper Network Topology
  • Image Data Augmentation
  • Weighted loss to account for class imbalance

6.1 Deeper Network Topology¶

In [33]:
# Initialize seed for random numbers
np.random.seed(1)
tf.random.set_seed(1)

# Sequential model
model_2 = Sequential()

# Input layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(128,128,3,)))
# Convolution layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(256, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Global Max Pool layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.GlobalMaxPool2D())
# Flatten layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
# Dense layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
# Dropout layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2))
# Dense layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
# Normalization layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# Output Layer
model_2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(12, activation='softmax')) # 12 predicted classes

# Initialize seed for random numbers
np.random.seed(1)
tf.random.set_seed(1)

# Sequential model
model_3 = Sequential()

# Input layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(128,128,3,)))

#### Data augmentation

model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.RandomFlip("horizontal", input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.RandomFlip("vertical", input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.1))
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.1))

# Convolution layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Normalization layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# 2D Convolution layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(256, kernel_size=(3,3), strides = (1,1), activation='relu'))
# Max Pool layer 
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
# Global Max Pool layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.GlobalMaxPool2D())
# Flatten layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
# Dense layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
# Dropout layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2))
# Dense layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
# Normalization layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
# Output Layer
model_3.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(12, activation='softmax')) # 12 predicted classes

# Function to calculate different metric scores of the classification model
def metrics_score_test(model,test,test_y,model_name=''):
    '''
    Inputs:
        model: classifier to predict values of X
        test: Independent features in test sets
        test_y: Dependent variable in test sets
        model_name: Name of the model
    '''
    
    loss_test, accuracy_test, recall_test, precision_test = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
    # Calculate scores and save them in a dictionary
    score_dict = {'Model': model_name,
                  'Accuracy on test set': accuracy_test,
                  'Recall on test set': recall_test,
                  'Precision on test set': precision_test
                 }
    # Create a dataframe with scores
    scores = pd.DataFrame(score_dict,index=[0])

    # return the df
    return scores

8 Conclusion and key takeaways¶

The main conclusions are:

  • With this project we were able to classify plant's species from a photo. The accuracy is very good in training, validation and test sets, 0.95/0.91/0.92 respectively
  • We improve the performance of the model using several strategies that show being effective in Image Classification problems
    • Using a deeper network topology
    • Using image data augmentation
    • Using weighted class to account for class imbalance
  • The model correctly classifies the different images
  • However, some Black-grass and Loose Silky-bent images were not properly identified. There are a couple of reasons:
    • The Black-grass class has around 250 images compared with other classes with more than 600 images. Our data set is very unbalanced
    • Both plants are similar, and the Neural Network is not being able to create a good separation between the two classes
